Fight on the edge of the knife: MP3 players against mobiles.
We will advise you how to choose
While almost every mobile phone can play MP3 files, no MP3 player can make a phone call.
It is better to just buy a phone.
Still, there are plenty of reasons for a person to purchase a separate player.
The choice depends entirely on the method of use and the requirements of the future owner.
It’s probably hard to get a top-notch expensive turntable at home to listen to Maxim Turbulenc’s latest album.
On the one hand, such music products do not come out on LPs, and from a qualitative point of view, there is no objective reason for this.
However, if there are vinyls with art rock, jazz or blues in your shelves, you probably dream of such a turntable at least.
It is the same with music on the go, i.e. music compressed, in simple terms - music in MP3.
There are also price and quality categories.
For some, it may be unacceptable to spend eight thousand crowns on a player, just as a Pink Floyd fan may find it difficult to try on headphones for twenty crowns from the market.
Two extremes, between which there is enough space for everyone.
The choice is wide.
It also determines the battery life
Some high-end music players can handle much more than just playing music, but what most mobile phones do by no means.
No other device is as versatile as the phone.
In addition to the primary functions, telephony and texting, he can play music and video, record both, has a better, worse camera and can even navigate.
And when we take into account smartphones and communicators, you will also have a small computer in your pocket.
It's a small miracle, because no fridge can grill and no TV can take pictures.
The universality of the mobile also brings disadvantages.
The more features you use on your mobile, the sooner the indicator on the display sends you to the charger.
And playing music is one of the biggest energy eaters.
Few phones can play music for more than ten to twelve hours, usually much less.
In this regard, music players (especially the simplest ones) are significantly more powerful.
In the case of cheap mobile phones, you should expect that they will not play for more than a few hours.
If you still call here and there, get another charger to work for sure - this also applies to more expensive devices.
MP3 players will not have this problem, even the worst ones will last at least 9 hours of continuous operation on a single charge.
Another problem arises when recording music to a mobile phone.
Unfortunately, only a limited number of devices have a universal USB connector, and moreover, not every one of them can be directly connected to the computer without special software.
Of course, it is possible to record music directly to a memory card, but few card readers can cope without reduction with the miniature memory cards that are used in mobile phones.
With the exception of iPods, you don’t need any special software.
Just fill the device with music via USB from your computer.
Most mobile phones and players will already create their own music library sorted by the name of the artist, album title, genre or user rating.
Some devices display only the tree structure of directories similar to Windows Explorer, and some are able to do both (iriver, Samsung, Sony, Cowon, smartphones with an operating system).
Players are easier to use, mobiles are more capable
When choosing a specific device, be especially interested in battery life, memory capacity, quality and type of audio output and, of course, the comfort of control.
If your music is primarily a backdrop and you listen to it every day for a short time, for example in a tram, then any mobile phone that plays MP3 will be enough for you.
Almost any mobile phone can do that.
You don’t even have to watch what music formats your phone or player can do.
MP3 can handle all and the vast majority of the music that gets to you will be in this format.
It is one of the most widely used and in addition to it, the vast majority of devices can also handle music in WMA format.
Less common is AAC (the format used by Apple and its iPods).
Better mobile phones also allow, for example, the purchase of music online.
Simply visit the relevant website of the operator (or other provider) and purchase the song or album via the mobile internet.
This service in itself could be a strong argument for the purchase of a music mobile phone.
Unfortunately, the offer of operators is poor and is usually limited only to quick-fermented radio hits.
The prices are also not the lowest.
However, it is generally assumed that this way of selling music (whether via GSM, the Internet or wireless Internet) in the future will dominate the music industry.
Most people carry their cell phones with them all the time.
Whenever you feel like listening to something, you can feel the phone in your pocket, while the MP3 player lies forgotten at home.
However, it also depends on whether you always carry headphones or at least wired handsfree with you.
If not, you can use the integrated speaker, which has almost every mobile, but only a minimum of MP3 players.
Probably the biggest advantage of music phones will be the price for many.
The cheapest ones usually cost under three thousand.
For three and four thousand crowns you will already get a very decent walkman.
Most of the time, however, you will be limited by the absence of an output to normal headphones.
The best and most technically equipped phones even with a 3.5 mm jack for ordinary headphones cost up to fifteen thousand.
The advantage of the players is, among other things, easy operation.
The simplest - not necessarily the cheapest (see our selection) - players can control really everyone.
The minimum of functions, the similarity of the control with a previously common cassette player or perhaps a turntable is obvious.
There is no risk of a collision in the form of an accidentally switched on mobile Internet and subsequently a giant account for data transmission.
Which device to use
Even the cheapest mobile phones (e.g. Vodafone 527) usually have a slot for removable memory cards (type M2, microSD, etc.).
Even with the purchase of the corresponding card, you will fit into two thousand crowns.
But be careful.
For basic models, only cards with a maximum capacity of 2 GB are supported.
Only the most expensive ones can cope with 8 GB of memory cards.
If you already have a mobile phone and want to buy a cheap MP3 player, reach for Cowon, Creativa, Sony, Samsung, Emgeton or iriver.
Depending on the capacity (max. 2 GB), you do not have to spend more than CZK 1,100.
If you are one of the more demanding listeners, rather reach for specialized mobiles - walkmans (Sony Ericsson, some Nokias and Samsungs).
These devices have separate control buttons for MP3 and thus the comfort of the operator is close to a separate MP3 player.
The furthest is Sony Ericsson, whose walkman phones have the same user interface as separately sold MP3 players.
The same service and in the same price category up to four thousand crowns, but with a larger memory capacity (up to 16 GB) and battery life (usually 15 hours, up to a maximum of 35 hours), will take MP3 players away from the above brands.
The first virtual operator will arrive in the Czech Republic this year.
Maybe.
The mobile market in the Czech Republic is quite developed and our operators offer virtually all services as their partners in Western Europe.
Yet something is missing here - a virtual operator that would make the classics cheaper.
Maybe he won't be long.
We have written many times about the fact that Czech operators are among the most expensive in Europe.
Moreover, this was also confirmed by the CTU, which pointed out that the price of SMS is higher in our country than in the rest of the Union.
Following the latest steps of the European Commission in the field of roaming charges regulation, a paradoxical situation may arise - for some customers of Czech mobile operators, SMS from abroad will be cheaper than at home.
How is it possible that prices in the Czech Republic are so high compared to Europe?
The answer is simple, there is no competition that really wants to fight.
It may sound paradoxical, because we have three mobile networks and penetration is well over 100%.
Mobile operators, on the other hand, like to boast that the Czech market is extremely competitive.
Pavel Dvo<0xC5><0x99>ák, Chairman of the Council of the Czech Telecommunication Office (<0xC4><0x8C>T<0xC3><0x9A>), often echoes them in this, who has said several times in the past that there is no place for another operator in the Czech Republic.
It is probably true that the classic operator with its own network probably does not have much chance (after all, it would probably be difficult to search for frequencies).
But there is another option - a virtual operator.
It was the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market that brought a significant reduction in prices, to which then even classic operators had to react.
However, even before the entry of the strikers such as Tesco Mobile or Virgin Mobile into the market, similar voices were heard in the UK as in our country.
But it turned out that the place for such operators is and can be really successful.
We don’t have to go too far for examples.
In February this year, we informed you about the launch of the virtual operator Mobilking in Poland.
In just six months, the operator has managed to gain more than 100,000 customers and become the fifth largest operator there.
At the same time, behind Mobilking is the financial group Penta, which in the Czech Republic owns, among other things, U:fona.
The advantage of virtual operators is the ability to focus on a much more specific target group.
In order to operate effectively, they need much fewer customers than a conventional operator.
They do not incur relatively high costs for the construction, operation and maintenance of the mobile network.
In the world, virtual operators are usually profiled as low-cost - they offer cheap calls and SMS, which is often balanced by a narrower range of services.
For example, Tesco Mobile in the UK offers SMS at least half cheaper than its competitors.
However, as the example of Mobilking in Poland shows, betting on a fresh target group can also be quite a good move.
This operator focuses specifically on men.
“The right guys choose Mobilking – an operator they like and can trust,” says David Seibertz, CEO of Mobile Entertainment Company, which operates the virtual operator.
It is difficult to say whether a similar concept as in Poland could be found in our country.
Vodafone spokesman Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> doubts this: "The Czech market is relatively small for the segment approach on which most virtual operators are based.
In addition, it is relatively saturated in terms of service offerings."
In the Czech Republic without a chance, say mobile operators
But it seems almost certain that if there is a virtual mobile operator in the Czech Republic, it will not be Mobilking.
"We are talking about the expansion of this successful project, but in the Czech Republic the negotiations do not look very promising.
Rather, Mobilking will be launched in other countries of our region," Jana Studni<0xC4><0x8D>ková, a spokeswoman for the Penta financial group, told Mobil.cz in a telephone interview.
Indirectly, it confirmed that the existing mobile operators in the Czech Republic are definitely not inclined to this idea.
Rather, they try to do everything so that no potential competitor arises.
The GTS Novera Group has been interested in launching a virtual mobile operator for a long time, which would like to take another step towards becoming a real competitor of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 in the field of corporate customers.
“We have a great interest in being able to offer our customers not only fixed but also mobile telecommunications services.
And the sooner the better.
We have repeatedly discussed this possibility with all Czech mobile operators.
We have already made progress with some of them," said Pavel Kaidl, a spokesman for the group.
Maybe he's looking forward to better times.
From unofficial information, it seems that the first virtual operator should be expected by the end of the year.
For now, however, its creation is accompanied by an impenetrable wall of silence.
"At the moment, we do not believe that there is room on the Czech market for the creation of a full-fledged virtual operator.
The Czech market is very specific compared to other markets.
So far, we have not been approached by any entity with a comprehensive and serious project in this area," Vlastimil Sr<0xC5><0xA1>e<0xC5><0x88> from the press department of Telef<0xC3><0xB3>nica O2 told Mobil.cz.
Other operators also refer to the specificity of the Czech market.
T-Mobile spokesman Martina Kemrová adds in rare agreement with the O2 statement: "We have not yet seen any viable and mutually beneficial business project on which to build further."
“It’s hard to have a virtual operator on T-Mobile by the end of the year.
At this point, we would have to have a concrete agreement on the table to be able to think in this short term.”
Vodafone is focusing its attention on meeting the requirements of its own 3G license.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> says: "We are open to dealing with potential virtual operators, especially in the area of cost-sharing and infrastructure.
This is what we consider to be the most beneficial from the customer’s point of view.
Vodafone’s main strategy in this area is to find a partner to build a shared network for fast mobile internet.”
Responsible authorities - with operators one hand
The procedure of mobile operators can be easily understood, the entry of another operator would mean an increase in competition, would lead to a decrease in prices and thus to a decrease in their profits.
So why make it easier for such a competitor?
The fact that when operators are interested in something, they are able to pull by one rope, is also evidenced by the tugs around the formation of U:fon.
Probably the greatest pressure towards CTU was at the time of the creation of U:fon by T-Mobile.
This is evidenced by publicly available information from the CTU website.
Now, however, U:fon is useful as an argument for not allowing a virtual operator.
Martina Kemrová said: "The competitive environment of the mobile market has recently been enhanced by the entry of the fourth mobile operator into the market.
Given the nature of the mobile market in the Czech Republic, it is clear that the entry of another player would place high demands on him and, above all, on his services."
However, given this approach of mobile operators, the complete lack of interest of the Czech regulatory authorities is striking.
It is not just the position of CTU, which unfortunately in the Czech Republic - unlike the UK and other developed countries - does not have the power to interfere with competition.
These belong exclusively to the Office for the Protection of Competition (<0xC3><0x9A>OHS).
But he took his typical approach to the whole issue.
“The entry of the virtual operator into the mobile market would be possible after the conclusion of a contract between the mobile operator and the virtual operator for the rental of the necessary infrastructure.
No such contract has been concluded so far, since the offer of potential candidates was probably not interesting enough for classical operators," Kristián Chalupa from the Department of External Relations of the Office of the OOHS said in response to our question.
From the representatives of operators, such a statement is probably not surprising.
From the authority that is supposed to represent the interests of consumers and, among other things, to ensure that no one abuses their position in the market, this is more than respectable.
Especially when Kristián Chalupa adds: "Outside where virtual operators normally operate, we can see that their entry into the market has contributed to lower prices for mobile phone services."
Apparently, however, the pressure on the correct functioning of the market environment and the drop in prices are not among the interests of the Office.
In fact, shocking on the whole case is the touching convergence of the three mobile operators, which results from their reactions.
The question of whether it is really just a coincidence is offered entirely by itself.
Just like the exact same price of petrol at gas stations, it is certainly only a matter of chance and a fierce competitive struggle.
"The Office has found no evidence of anti-competitive conduct in this case and therefore has no reason to intervene in any way.
None of the operators has a dominant position and therefore does not have adequate increased responsibility for its conduct on the market.
The necessary tools for opening the mobile market to virtual operators are likely to be lacking for the telecommunication regulator as well," Chalupa said in a statement.
The interpretation of the dominant position in the market is one of the many controversial points.
Of course, there is an analysis of relevant markets prepared by CTU, according to which telecommunications are the only market in terms of competition.
In such a market, of course, none of the Czech operators has a dominant position.
However, some legal experts offer a different view - to create a virtual operator, you always need the consent of the network operator.
And the mobile operator - quite logically - has a monopoly on its network.
So in a certain segment it must necessarily be dominant.
Even if we do not accept this argument, it should be at least a warning to the Office of the OOHS that the three mobile operators are acting in a conspicuously similar way.
At the same time, complaints from a number of interested parties (including GTS Novera) show that they encounter very similar obstacles when dealing with all operators.
The imposition of liability on CTU is then a fairly common trick in telecommunications, which the Office gives away from the whole matter.
We have met him on several similar occasions.
Unfortunately, until the recently adopted amendment to the Telecommunications Act, the extension of the CTU’s powers to the area of competition in telecommunications failed to assert itself, although many experts promised to improve the situation.
This must be known by the representatives of the OOHS more than well, but apparently their interests are elsewhere.
It's okay when no one's looking
At the same time, the functioning of some pseudo-virtual operators remains unnoticed, of which there are several in the Czech mobile networks.
These are companies that issue their own price lists of mobile phone services, but they are only partially public.
These are usually multi-level marketing companies.
Its own mobile phone services are offered by Amway, Bohemia Telecom, Starlife and many others.
The prices of these companies usually reach only the chosen ones.
The magic lies in the fact that the company acts as a classic company customer towards the operator, who orders a large number of SIM cards.
As a significant customer, he will then receive special price (and other) offers.
The problem is that the trading conditions of all Czech mobile operators prohibit a similar resale.
"If there are cases you are talking about, it could be a violation of the terms and conditions that we would deal with and could result in termination of cooperation with the company," Martina Kemrová answered our question on this issue.
However, it is quite unlikely that such an activity would not be carried out by responsible people from mobile operators.
In particular, in the case of the three mentioned companies, there may be thousands of customers.
However, none of the operators will be able to prevent such a procedure.
They have considerable profits from the activities of these companies and, unlike real virtual operators, they do not threaten them with their own official marketing.
Miroslav <0xC4><0x8C>epick<0xC3><0xBD> points out possible problems: "The law allows such speculation, but only a negligible percentage of customers use the services of these companies.
In addition, they must accept that the SIM card in their phone is not in their name, so they cannot have it fully as regular customers of mobile operators.
That should be the least strange thing.
In addition, another question opens up for the <0xC3><0x9A>OHS.
If mobile operators turn a blind eye to a similar procedure, why block the creation of a virtual operator?
It should be added that the Office has relatively strong powers to detect such activities, and if it does not want to, it may not be satisfied with the explanation of the operators that they have no idea about anything like this and their business conditions prohibit it.
When we won't be the most expensive
As it has already happened several times in the text, the entry of virtual operators into the mobile market has brought a noticeable decrease in prices for services.
In virtually all countries where virtual operators originated, classical operators tried to more or less prevent their creation.
The arguments used by them were practically identical - too small or over-saturated market, problems with the quality of services, etc.
In developed countries, however, it was at this point that regulators intervened, defending not the interests of mobile operators, but their customers.
Whether by formal measures or informal pressure, they then achieved the creation of the first virtual operator and more were stacked on it.
Unfortunately, the Czech regulatory authorities are shifting the whole case like a hot potato.
We cannot get rid of the impression from our experience that ambiguities in competences are more than useful to them in these cases.
But let's not throw flint in the rye.
If the behind-the-scenes information is correct and the virtual operator is really coming soon, the Czech mobile market may be moving again.
If one of the operators admitted the creation of a virtual mobile operator, it will be difficult for the OOHS to remain indifferent to the rejection (discrimination) of other interested parties.
And maybe we'll stop calling more than the rest of Europe.
