Prague’s public transport will be on the chip for the first time on Wednesday
Wednesday 1st October 2008 will go down in the history of the Prague Transport Company as the date when the first passengers will enter the metro, trams and buses, who will have an electronic coupon in their pocket instead of a paper ticket.
At the moment, it can be purchased by about one hundred thousand people who own an Opencard chip card.
Passengers can buy a 30-day and 90-day and annual coupon (this will apply from January 1, 2009) and have it uploaded to their smart card in the information centers and workplaces of the Transport Company in the metro stations Muzeum, M<0xC5><0xAF>stek, Nádra<0xC5><0xBE><0xC3><0xAD> Hole<0xC5><0xA1>ovice, And<0xC4><0x9B>l, Roztyly, Let<0xC5><0x88>any, Kobylisy, Rajská zahrada, Ka<0xC4><0x8D>erov and Luka.
Coupons can also be purchased online from yesterday on the website of the Transport Company www.dpp.cz.
The service was used by more than 400 customers in the afternoon.
Those who start using the online store can finally forget about the dispensing windows in metro stations, where they have had to regularly stand in long queues on paper tickets.
They buy the coupon online and upload it to the Opencard card in one of the thirteen branches of the Municipal Library.
"At these places, passengers have a counter with trained staff, which will help those interested with online shopping and also upload the purchased coupon to their card," said Martin Opatrn<0xC3><0xBD>, a spokesman for the project.
In addition to libraries, it will be possible to upload electronic coupons to Opencard also in self-service vending machines, which are mounted in several subway vestibules.
What do these machines look like?
They are red, reminiscent of ticket markers and passengers may have already noticed them in the metro stations Roztyly, Bud<0xC4><0x9B>jovická, I. P. Pavlova, Florenc and Vltavská.
"There are five of them in the city now, but there should be eighty by the end of the year," he added.
Coupon will check the place of the driver automat
Operating the machines, which will start working tomorrow, is simple.
Just insert the Opencard chip card into them and the previously paid coupon will be loaded on it itself.
Electronic coupons from tomorrow apply not only in the capital, but also in its vicinity.
That is, in suburban trains and bus lines with the number 300 to 499, which go to the capital mainly residents of the Central Bohemian municipalities.
"In the trains included in the Prague Integrated Transport, the conductors are equipped with card readers, with which they check the time and zone validity of coupons," explained Filip Drápal from the Ropid organization, which compiles timetables for Prague public transport.
Suburban buses have card readers built into the cash register at the driver.
Upon boarding, it is therefore necessary not only to show the chip card to the driver, but also to attach the Opencard to the designated place on the side of the cash register.
This will allow the driver to check the validity of the vouchers.
“If a passenger needs to verify the validity of a ticket, there’s nothing easier than asking the driver for this information,” Drápal added.
