Even rats have feelings.
When a rat or cockroach runs away from danger, does that mean that they too feel fear?
Neuroscientist Joseph LeDoux believes that even animals have feelings.
But how could it be verified that they feel the same way when they behave like us?
In the online magazine "Edge" for several years, the contributions of well-known scientists have been published.
SPIEGEL ONLINE presents selected answers to the question "What do you think is true without you being able to prove it?"
I believe that animals have feelings and other states of consciousness without me or anyone else being able to prove it, when we can’t even prove that other people have consciousness.
But in this case, we can at least hope, because all human brains have the same basic configuration.
But as soon as we begin to engage with another species and open up questions of perception or general consciousness, we enter into an impassable terrain, because the hardware does not match.
When a rat gets into danger, it does what many other animals do: it pretends to be dead, flees, or attacks.
Humans behave in a similar way, from which some scientists conclude a similar subjective experience.
I don't believe that, though.
Two aspects of brain structure make it difficult to transfer our subjective experience to that of animals.
This is partly because the circuits associated with human consciousness almost always include the lateral prefrontal cortex (due to its share of short-term memory and executive or control functions).
This vast area is much more developed in humans than in other primates, and appears to be completely absent in other creatures.
At least for those aspects of our consciousness that depend on the prefrontal cortex, among them knowledge of who we are and the ability to plan and make decisions, there is reason to believe that man is different even from other primates.
Another dramatic peculiarity could be hidden by the linguistic nature of man: because so much of his perception is connected with language, it is often said that consciousness depends on it.
In this case, we could exclude animals.
But even if consciousness did not matter about language, language would certainly influence it, so that animal consciousness, however constructed, would probably differ from most states of our consciousness.
Therefore, it is difficult to find out what consciousness looks like in other animals.
When, as something internal and subjective, it cannot be measured or, due to special hardware, analyzed on the basis of our own experience, we are faced with great problems.
Most of my conclusions relate to the content of conscious experience, but there is another aspect of consciousness that should be more scientifically accessible.
It would be possible to study processes in the consciousness of animals regardless of their content, and this is exactly what happens in studies of short-term memory in primates, especially on the example of visualization.
But this approach, pursued by Christof Koch and Francis Crick, focuses on neural correlates of consciousness rather than causal mechanisms: both may be identical, but they may not be.
Interestingly, this approach also emphasizes the importance of the non-frontal cortex for the realization of visualization.
What does this mean for feelings?
I deduce them from the fact that the emotional system, such as the fear system, is activated in the brain conscious of its own activity.
What we refer to as “fear” is therefore the mental state we find ourselves in when the activity of a defense system located in the brain (or its consequences, such as bodily reactions) makes use of operational memory.
Seen from this angle, feelings are closely related to those areas of the cortex that are characterized by primates, and especially humans.
