Debate on bilingualism: immersion in English
In this issue of Focused on Education, Bruce Fuller and Lance T. Izumi will discuss the position of candidates for bilingual education.
Lance T. Izumi, a Californian academic and director of education at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy, is co-author of “Worse Than You Think: Why the Middle Class Needs to Choose Schools.”
Reaching out to Hispanic voters effectively is a tricky business.
Barack Obama’s educational agenda proves it.
Obama’s campaign notes that “African-American and Hispanic students are significantly less likely to graduate than white students,” which is true.
To combat such performance differences, Obama’s education agenda promotes, among other things, “transient bilingual education” for those who are just learning English.
The question for Barack Obama, however, remains whether his commitment to bilingual education, which emphasizes the use of languages other than English in the classroom, is stronger than his interest in reducing performance differences.
Take, for example, Sixth Street Prep, a charter elementary school in East Los Angeles County.
The students of this school are in the vast majority of cases Hispanics from low-income families.
More than a third of students, many of whom have only recently arrived, are still learning English.
Nevertheless, in the state tests of mathematics in 2008, an incredible one hundred percent of fourth-graders reached the highest level.
Almost the same amazing ninety-three percent of fourth graders have reached the highest level in state tests of English language and literature.
This incredible success was achieved by a method other than the one preferred by Obama.
Sixth Street emphasizes control and practice, constant assessment of abilities, and an unexcused approach.
Further, and this should be noted, according to Linda Mikels, director of Sixth Street, the school’s pedagogical approach for those who are just learning English is “total immersion.”
Immersion in English emphasizes the almost privileged use of English in teaching.
Ms. Mikels, who is against bilingual education, told me: “We had a tremendous success with a brand new student from Mexico – after twelve months you would walk into a class and not know who it was.”
"It works," she said, "it works for us."
Would Obama take a school like Sixth Street Prep as a model for what other schools with large proportions of Hispanic and English-speaking students should look like?
The school’s results should make the answer to this question self-evident, but the educational agenda of its own party (the National Education Association has been a longtime advocate of bilingual education) and its own consistent support for bilingual education obscure the prediction of Obama’s answer.
While Obama agrees that immigrants should learn English, he recently trivialized the matter by saying that people should stop worrying about “only English” laws.
Instead, "you should make sure your children speak Spanish," he said.
If Obama really wants to erase performance differences, he should think carefully about the educational patterns that work, rather than mock them and trivialize them.
