Pride and Obstacles to Black Life in a Separate City
Hidden among the sprawling amusement parks of Greater Orlando, a few miles from everything shiny, noisy and huge, lies a quiet city where the pride and rigor of African-American life comes to life.
Eatonville, the first completely black city to be incorporated into the state and where Zora Neale Hurston spent her childhood, is no longer as simple as she described it in 1935: "the city of five lakes, three croquettes, three hundred brown skins, three hundred good swimmers, plenty of quail, two schools."
Now it is a place of pilgrimage.
Alice Walker, Toni Morrison and Ruby Dee came to the annual Eatonville festival Zora! to pay tribute to Hurston, the most famous female writer of the Harlem Renaissance.
The city she described remains a sideshow, though she made it a stopover for tourists by including it in a Florida tourist guide created by the Federal Writers Project during the economic crisis.
It’s still as independent, dignified, and private as it was in the 1930s, when Hurston wrote that rural blacks in Florida often resisted and didn’t share their true feelings with a white man who “knows so little about us that he doesn’t even know what he’s missing.”
Even today, in a year when the black presidential candidate, Senator Barack Obama, is calling for an open debate about race, many of the residents here remain wary of foreign views.
“We pay a lot of attention to how our story is told,” said Hortense Jones, 59, who has lived here since birth and is a member of the oldest parish in the city.
"It must be right."
Eatonville has long been characterized as a paradox of triumph and effort.
It is both a historical model of black ascendancy and a community of nearly 2,400 people, where the poverty rate is twice the national average.
It is a center of literature, but also an oak shaded example of Southern rural black culture – sometimes despised, sometimes praised – that arose from American slavery.
Not surprisingly, the locals are both proud and protective.
And worries about Eatonville really began with Zora, which is the only way Hurston is called here.
She introduced the world to her hometown through heartwarming books such as Mules and Men (1935) and Their Eyes Were Watching God (1937).
The five paragraphs of the Florida tourist guide turned the city a little bit into Route 17, which leads through the often-missing center of Florida, a stage of black history and human drama.
With the birth of the great drum in both life and literature, Hurston led readers to the shop of the first Eatonville mayor, Joe Clark, and then turned to more personal places.
"To the left of the road," she wrote, "is a white, brown-decorated modern national school with well-maintained yards and playgrounds that Howard Miller always looks after, even though he can't read or write much."
She also mentioned the widow’s new husband, Dash, and wrote that Lee Glenn “sells drinks of all kinds and anything that fits in a one-hour hotel.”
So in just a few hundred words, Hurston linked Eatonville to self-government, but also to illiteracy, remarriage, and sex.
This was obviously not a typical Fodor's publishing house.
In fact, it was not a portrait that everyone would appreciate.
“Zora said it the way it was,” says 90-year-old Ella Dinkins, one of Johnson’s girls who made Hurston immortal by quoting men who sang dirty songs about their beauty.
"Some people didn't like it," she added.
Hurston is still remembered here as a chippy freak who often returned after her family moved to Jacksonville, Florida.
Seventy-seven-year-old Augustus Franklin remembers that most of the time, when she arrived in the city, she arrived unannounced in a huge Chevrolet, smoking and wearing pants in a city that is still proud of decent dress.
Most residents were fascinated, Franklin said, but many grinned.
"People have always liked to see Dawn," Franklin said.
But, he added, rocking in a chair on the back terrace overlooking Lake Sabelia, where Hurston was most likely baptized, "never stayed too long."
When Hurston died in 1960, she was poor and her books were taken out of print.
Eatonville seemed to have forgotten it, along with the rest of the world.
Although she was once a literary star, a contemporary of Langston Hughes and the only black woman at Barnard College in the 1920s, she was buried in an unmarked grave in Fort Pierce, Florida, where she had previously lived.
There were no major mourning ceremonies or large public readings in Eatonville.
“I don’t think they understood its meaning to the world or its legacy,” said Valerie Boyd, author of Hurston’s 2003 biography Wrapped in Rainbows.
The change came in the 1980s.
Orange County officials wanted to stretch the city's five-lane highway instead of Kennedy Boulevard, which is the local two-lane main road.
Orlando's ascent has already pushed Interstate 4 through the western edge of the city.
The proposal came at a time when Eatonville was still getting out of a difficult historical period.
Forced integration, along with other things, ended the relatively idyllic isolation of this community.
In the 1950s, the struggle to mix races brought hatred to the doorstep of the community.
"At that time, a bunch of white guys, they came in and threw oranges and stuff at the people who were sitting on the side," Franklin said.
"Actually, we had a lady who was killed.
They threw watermelon out of the car."
In a 1955 letter to The Orlando Sentinel, Hurston questioned the Supreme Court's demand for forced integration and said Brown's decision against the Education Chamber was "more offensive to my race than glorious."
Residents now claim that the desegregation of schools, although positive in some areas, has reduced cohesion in Eatonville and undermined the courage of the local youth.
“Black kids were used to hugging — I remember — you hugged your teacher in the morning, you hugged your teacher in the evening,” said N.Y. Nathiri, daughter of Elly Dinkins and executive director of the nonprofit group Preserve the Eatonville Community.
It took as long as the teachers and students came from the same place, she added.
"You don't hug your white teacher because your white teacher -- I mean, there's a cultural barrier," Ms. Nathiri said.
Civil rights, however, has helped create space for many more Zora Neale Hurstons—black writers, actors, and artists who, like her, have risen above prejudice with frivolous self-confidence and quotes such as “How can anyone deny the pleasure of my presence!
I don't understand."
In 1975, Alice Walker arrived at Hurston's unmarked grave and began fighting to revive her reputation.
Five years later, Robert E. Hemenway's acclaimed biography of Hurston re-introduced her to the American canon.
The highway project arrived just as Eatonville's most famous daughter had found the ramp lights again.
The former Hurston neighbors now regarded her as a savior.
To show what might happen to its highway, the community began planning the Hurston Festival in 1988.
Thousands of fans arrived for the inaugural event two years later, and every January many return to celebrate.
After a few years, the state withdrew from the highway proposal.
"These five highway streams have resurrected, you would say, directly detonated, real civic pride," Nathiri said.
Boyd put it simply: "Dawn saved Eatonville."
The victory over the highway project helped to change the image of the city.
Outsiders such as Rachelle Munson, a lawyer who began attending the church in 1993, began to appear in larger numbers, and residents began to reassess the past.
Eatonville joined the National Historical Register in 1998.
A new one-story library (named after Hurston, of course) opened in 2006 on the newly paved and embellished Kennedy Boulevard.
Today, Eatonville remains a Florida anomaly: just six miles from downtown Orlando can sometimes act as a sunken alley in the summer rain, as small as it was when it was founded with only 27 black families in the 1880s.
(He is now 90 percent black.)
Strangers who come to seek the story and meaning of Eatonville are still often treated with caution.
Permission for most interviews is required in advance, and certain things - such as wall paintings in the oldest church in Eatonville, painted by whites and depicting blacks in the fields - are not allowed to be photographed.
Many in Eatonville, like Jones, a bold, self-assured teacher who likes deep red, still fear that their isolated community will not be properly understood.
And as the Hurston Festival grew, so did domestic pride.
Especially young people tend to see Eatonville the way Hurston saw her entire race: beautiful, with problems, and so on, but no better, no worse, and just as proud, creative, hardworking, foolish, and diverse as other American races and ethnicities.
Franklin's nephew, 18-year-old Edwin Harvey, has a genuine love for the community as he plans to return to Eatonville after college to work for the local government or the police, who he says would use some help.
And even younger ones, such as the eleven-year-old Winter Park twins Alondra and Alex Kenon, seem to have learned to describe Eatonville correctly.
"Most people, if they just walk through here, they think, 'Uh, this town is nothing against the others,'" Alondra Kenon said recently after church.
"But if you really stop and look at history for a moment, it's a very nice city."
Here in New York, we all speak fluently financially
At first glance, nothing has changed.
If tourists in Manhattan stayed away from newspaper stands and giant TV screens in Times Square, they wouldn’t realize they were standing in the middle of a storm.
They would never have guessed that in the bee hive of offices above their heads, every day, the bankers and investment fund managers who monopolize New York City are having the worst “bad day at the office” since the 1929 crisis.
Messengers still rattle metal carts on the sidewalks and carry muffin casseroles to breakfast meetings.
The Spaniards are still moving among the skyscrapers and wearing, like human mules, fifty ironed shirts hanging from the pendulums on their backs.
Office rats are still waiting in line for their morning bagel at the street dining stalls, and it is still not possible to get a yellow cab on a weekday between four and seven in the afternoon.
It didn’t seem like a crisis at all until, with all the talk of pessimism, I decided to set up a savings account on Thursday afternoon.
Despite the fact that I had timed this task to cover the late afternoon siesta at my local branch of JP Morgan Chase, there were already about twenty people waiting in line.
Not in front of checkout windows to pick up or store cash, but in front of a counter where older clients order checkbooks, tourists ask for directions to the Macy's mixed-goods store, and new customers set up accounts.
Most of the people before me, as I learned from Starr, my “licensed personal banker,” came for the same reason I did.
However, compared to me, they have already taken their savings from smaller banks in places where they came from, such as New Jersey, Pennsylvania or Staten Island.
They took money from so-called “thrifts” (a bit like construction savings banks), money unions, and those types of savings banks whose branches operate in only one state and which claim to take care of their customers as a family.
In the past year, 15 such banks have quietly failed.
A few days ago, Washington Mutual, a bank with $327 billion in assets, went bankrupt, and as New Yorkers were returning home for the weekend on Friday night, another bank, Wachovia, with $440 billion in assets, was trying to catch a rescue buyer.
The employees of the offices and shops that stood in front of me and were afraid of another collapse moved their cash to a bank that is perceived as a safe haven and that does most of the rescuing on Wall Street.
Over the past week, ordinary New Yorkers have learned a lot financially.
A woman in my local Chinese supermarket spoke on the phone and spoke to Lehman Borthers, that bankrupt bank, and her emaciated chief executive Dick Fulda with such familiarity as if she were gossiping about a lazy colleague.
And Lyn, the uniformed, roughly 50-year-old housekeeper of my apartment building, changed the subject of our ordinary conversation — Brad, Angelina, or my grocery delivery.
After my visit to the bank, she told me, “I now have my savings in money market funds.
I moved it, I won't risk it."
