Drivers repeatedly caught with alcohol in the blood will have to install "alcolock"
The Ministry of the Interior requires that a driver with three administrative penalties for driving under the influence of alcohol must install a system in his car that will prevent him from starting the car intoxicated or if he does not breathe.
The proposal became known in June this year and is now included in the annual report of the Supreme State Prosecutor’s Office, according to which it is a pilot project that will last one year.
Its goal is to return the driver behind the wheel, so drivers will also have to take a road re-education course.
In addition to the National Transport Safety Office, the Directorate-General for Transport (DGT) and the Foundation of the Institute of Technology for Automobile Safety (FITSA) will also be involved in this experience.
According to statistics, between 30 and 75 percent of motorists accused of driving drunk more than once get behind the wheel again in this state.
Alcolock should prevent this, as it is a system connected to the vehicle that measures the level of alcohol in the exhaled air and prevents the car from starting if the driver does not breathe before or if there is a higher than allowed concentration of alcohol.
Its price exceeds 1,000 euros and it would have to be paid by the culprit himself.
A study carried out in the USA in 2007 showed that for vehicles equipped with this device, in the first year after the introduction, there was a 65 % reduction in infractions.
In Spain, it is estimated that 115 lives could be saved every year.
The measure is limited to administrative sanctions for two reasons: to address this behaviour before it results in a criminal offence.
And in order to facilitate its introduction, since the legislation can be carried out in the usual way, the necessary regulation of criminal provisions, however, requires an amendment of the law.
The device is not yet available in any sales version on the Spanish market, although it has already been trial-installed in some industrial and public service vehicles.
Tomorrow, the Congress of Deputies will vote on the PSOE (Spanish Workers' Socialist Party) proposal, which recommends installing this system on school buses, as is the case in France.
