Talking from sleep
Some kids talk at night.
I don’t mean the ones who wake up and tell us something that happened the day before, but the children who talk while they sleep.
When it happens for the first time, it may scare you, but in reality it’s meaningless.
This is a harmless sleep disorder called somniloquia.
It is quite common, especially in children and adolescents.
I'm sure many of you have been told that he spoke in his sleep at night.
This phenomenon can occur very sporadically (for example, once in a lifetime with high fevers), or with greater regularity (every day, once a week, once every few months ...), the next day the child does not remember anything.
There is not just one reason for his arrival.
It is often associated with other sleep disorders, such as nightmares, night rage, enuresis nocturna (night help) or sleepwalking, but this may not be the case.
As mentioned earlier, it can often be accompanied by very high fevers, stressful or troubled situations.
In any case, this is a little-studied phenomenon.
The intensity with which it appears is also different.
The child can speak in a calm voice, say individual words, whisper, or just the opposite (screams, crying, long speeches...).
In cases where it manifests itself with great force, it would be appropriate for the child to observe and consult a specialist to see if he has any problem that causes him great anxiety and in this way manifests itself.
We have said that it is a harmless disorder, therefore it is not treated only if it is associated with another sleep disorder that can be treated (for example, if it is associated with apnea syndrome or with permanent stress).
However, we can do this by keeping in mind a few very simple preventive measures, such as:
Try not to disturb the child too much before he goes to sleep.
So look for calm games and avoid spooky or somewhat violent TV programs or series.
For very nervous children and those who are given work to relax, it is possible to use relaxation techniques that will help them gain some inner peace.
This will allow the child to sleep more soundly.
When somniloquy appears, try to keep calm.
Remind yourself that it is harmless to the child and that he will not remember anything from what happened the next day.
Helpful advice
Don't wake him.
It's useless because he's not conscious and you're interrupting his sleep.
Even when he speaks, he sleeps, and therefore he rests.
Remember that if several times in a row it seems to you that they are very worried, it would be advisable to turn to advice or find out what causes such anxiety in a child.
If he understands what he is saying (which is not so common), avoid the temptation to question him and draw information from him.
It will be of no use, because when he sleeps, he is not conscious to organize his thoughts.
In addition, you will hear what he says, but you do not know what he dreams about, and therefore why he says it, so be very careful how you interpret the information and what conclusions you come to.
Never tell a child that you can ask him his secrets at night.
Not even for fun.
This causes great anxiety.
Don’t worry, it’s not a bad thing, it’s just an episode that only lasts a few minutes.
