Interview - Blood that is safe again
Yesterday, Héma-Québec celebrated its tenth anniversary, and its president, Dr. Francine Décary, rightly rejoiced that Héma-Québec had become one of the most reliable and efficient blood suppliers in the world.
Above all, he has regained the public’s trust, which was seriously shaken by the blood-contaminated scandal of the 1980s and 1990s.
As is widely known, the national blood reserve administered by the Transfusion Department of the Canadian Red Cross was contaminated with the immune deficiency virus (HIV) and hepatitis C virus during the 1980s.
In view of this drama and the wave of public discontent, the Canadian Government launched a public inquiry in February 1994, chaired by Judge Horace Krever, aimed at explaining the circumstances that led to such a tragedy and making recommendations not to repeat such a disaster.
While Judge Krever delayed the submission of the report, some provinces put in place a committee to plan a new blood management system in Canada.
In Québec, the Gélineau Committee took up this role.
Following the Gélineau and Krever reports, two suppliers were set up in Canada: Hema-Quebec, which was to manage Quebec, and the Canadian Blood Society for supplying all provinces and both territories.
“When Hema-Québec began its activities in 1998, barely 38% of people still had confidence in the Québec blood system,” Dr. Décary recalls.
"The situation was deplorable.
Through continuous efforts to increase the safety of blood products and constant work in this area over the next years, we have regained public confidence," he says and proudly adds that at the beginning of 2008, almost 94% of the Québec population already trusted Héma-Quebec.
However, Dr. Décary does not lose sight of the fact that "trust is something very fragile."
Since its founding on 28 September 1998, Héma-Québec has applied the precautionary principle.
“At that time, we saw many cases of human-like mad cow disease in Europe, a new variant of the disease called Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease,” says a woman who has run the company since its founding in 1998.
"And we had no idea that this disease could spread through blood.
We therefore relied on one of the basic recommendations of the Krever and Gélineau reports, according to which, when we do not know and when the spread of a serious disease is at stake, in this case Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease, which is characterized by brain degeneration inevitably leading to death, an exclusionary measure must be taken.
In April 1999, we therefore refused blood to people who had been in the United Kingdom for more than one month since 1980.
A few years ago, it was safely proven that this disease is transmitted by blood.
So this episode showed us that sticking to the precautionary principle made sense.”
In 1999, a much more accurate technique for detecting HIV appeared on the market: nucleic acid (NAT) tests, which make it possible to detect the presence of the virus itself in donor blood, rather than the presence of antibodies on which the tests used before were based.
NAT tests have made it possible to shorten the deaf period that occurs between the moment of infection of the patient and the moment when our techniques can detect the first viruses in the blood, explains the specialist.
We were able to shorten this period to less than a week.
We’ve significantly reduced the risk that some donors could be infected without them knowing it and without us being able to figure it out.
These improvements have made it possible to significantly reduce the risk of getting AIDS through blood transfusions.
Today, one in 12 million people is at risk of getting HIV-contaminated blood.
“In other words, it means that 12 million blood products will need to be distributed before someone becomes infected with HIV.
Since Hema-Quebec distributes 400,000 to 500,000 blood products every year, it will take 24 years for the first case of HIV transmission through a blood product to occur.
I believe that today we can receive or prescribe a blood transfusion necessary for healing in complete peace," said the head of the Hema-Quebec leadership.
“The challenge for the next decade is to keep our products safe.
We never know what disease-causing elements may appear in the system.
Just last year, the chikungunya virus appeared on the island of Réunion, which, like the West Nile virus, is transmitted to the blood by stinging insects.
We need to be careful all the time," Dr Décary continues, stressing that in addition to safe supplies, Hema-Quebec must also count on sufficient supplies.
“The needs are growing as the population ages.
As a result of more aggressive cancer treatment, patients often need a new dose of red blood cells or platelets.
The aging of the population also has implications for the blood donor network, which on average consists of only 3% of Québecers who are eligible to donate.”
Each healthy person is at least 18 years old, meeting the criteria for admissibility, but can donate blood only once every 56 days, that is, six times a year.
On average, 14% of people who offer blood are not accepted, because they are, for example, carriers of AIDS or malaria, and if they have visited a country where mudslides are raging, they are excluded for a year.
“With this 3%, we can maintain a state that meets the needs of hospitals.
Deficiencies are very rare.
Members of the donor network, however, need to be supplemented in proportion to how they age and can no longer donate blood.
However, it is difficult to persuade people to give blood, especially to keep them and encourage them to become regular donors.
“Life is so unrestrained today that we rarely find an hour to donate blood.” – Francine Décary
With an annual budget of $297 million, Hema-Quebec supplies not only blood products, but also human tissue, such as bone grafts, heart valves, eyeballs, and skin, which is almost exclusively used for large burns.
These tissues are analysed, processed and frozen before they are stored at Hema-Quebec, which also manages the only public cord blood bank in Quebec.
The umbilical cord, previously considered a biomedical waste, abounds with blood rich in stem cells that can be used to treat serious diseases, such as leukemia.
“A few weeks ago, we celebrated the deposit of our 1,000th cord blood sample into the bank, and we expect to collect over 1,000 cord blood samples a year.
At the beginning of next year, we should start offering them for transplants," explains Dr. Décary, who describes the cord blood collection program as very popular.
"Some mothers are disappointed that they do not have access to it," because Hema-Québec does not have enough funds to offer this complex and expensive program to all hospitals in Québec.
