Letters: The Dishonored Land
It was Vic Toews, the ex-minister of "justice" (of irony) in Harper's cabinet, who last summer allowed himself to say of Louise Arbour that she was a "shame" for Canada.
To defame a woman who has fought tirelessly for justice, and who deserves all our admiration, says a lot about the Prime Minister’s entourage and Stephen Harper himself.
We have before us a government that, as the only one of all the Western countries involved, has not taken back to its homeland its citizen imprisoned in the Guantánamo concentration camp.
A government that takes no account of the fact that Omar Khadr was a young adolescent at the time of the alleged crimes.
The only government that, despite the fact that Canada has signed the Geneva Convention, denies its word and leaves a child soldier rotting in inhumane conditions.
The only one who relies on a parody of justice to judge the defendant's guilt.
Recall that UNICEF, Amnesty International and in particular the Association of Canadian Lawyers advocate the repatriation of Omar Khadr, so that he can wait for a fair trial in Canada.
The same government turns a blind eye to torture: it cares little that this young man is psychologically destroyed in the future, no doubt permanently, after so many years of torture.
