The shame, Mr. Toews, is in this renunciation, not elsewhere.
Opinions - Barrick Gold's Orwellian Discourse
In the September 17 issue, Le Devoir printed a letter from Patrick J. Garver, executive vice president of Canadian mining company Barrick Gold.
With Orwellian logic, he confirms that the world’s largest gold producer has launched a prosecution of three authors and a poor little publishing house for insulting honor with the aim of sparking a “transparent public debate” and demanding six million for them.
If it is true that judges are independent and impartial, they do not judge the truth, especially in the case of prosecution for insult to honour, but the law.
Unsurprisingly, Garver misses this crucial distinction altogether.
Or is it the best way for Barrick Gold to hold a public debate, to bankrupt anyone who dares to defend the opposite position?
Whatever the outcome, the authors and publisher of Noir Canada (Black Canada) will be forced to spend respectable sums of money to be ready to defend themselves and fight in a very unbalanced fight with an army of lawyers supported by the almost bottomless pockets of a mining company.
The tactic in these unbalanced battles, after all, often consists in ruining the defendants in order to enforce a conciliation procedure that will silence the opposing party and, moreover, terrify anyone who would dare to devote himself to this matter.
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public debate, it should have presented its view to public opinion.
Contrary to what is happening in several countries where Barrick Gold operates, in Canada the debate under normal circumstances lies in the exchange of ideas, and not in the stabbing of a baton.
The mining companies, therefore, were not enough to open their books, their documentation, and create a real debate through newspapers, media, publications, and the funding of independent scientific teams that could bring light to the matter.
Barrick Gold, however, does not seem to have confidence in public opinion and has been quick to reject petitions and letters in support of the authors of Noir Canada.
Perhaps Garver could explain how he can demand a "public debate" and at the same time despise the views of the same public?
In the vice president’s world, the word seems to refer only to high-paying lawyers, not to all Canadians; that’s a rather narrow term.
In a democracy, even the nazis have the right to speak.
Barrick Gold does not understand – or does not want to understand – that the public, which supports the authors and publishers of Noir Canada, does so primarily because they reject the brutal ways of mining society.
The public is ready to hear Barrick and judge the matter, but on the basis of a civilized exchange of arguments, not in what many perceive as a prosecution in which the defendant is to be silenced (in their prosecution of the "public debate", the company Barrick, by the way, has just filed an official appeal to the authors of Noir Canada, to re-state them officially...
Aside from Garver’s surreal speech, the prosecution initiated by Barrick Gold is a direct attack on the university’s freedom of inquiry and the search for truth, which are essential to any democratic society.
In general, it denies the right to quote credible sources and to debate the facts and interpretations that constitute the very basis of intellectual activity.
If, in a country like Canada, it is impossible to study and discuss topics that the world’s rich companies don’t like without facing repeated prosecution, who else will be able to do it?
If Barrick Gold really wanted a public and transparent debate, it could create one if it followed the scientific standards used by the authors of Noir Canada.
He's entitled to an answer.
The university environment we belong to has long been able to manage debates and disagreements and resolve conflicts.
Barrick Gold’s exaggerated lawsuit clearly shows that, despite what it claims, it has no desire to have a transparent debate.
It is a loss for the university world, as it is for the public debate in Canada, and it is time for governments to put in place measures to curb this type of unjustified prosecution.
Wall Street rescue operation: Democrats and Republicans understand each other
The Bush administration and congressional leaders, both Republicans and Democrats, finally reached an agreement yesterday on the largest economic rescue plan since the Great Depression of the 1930s.
A new version of the plan to use $700 billion to contain the financial crisis that has been plaguing Wall Street for months has yet to be approved by both chambers of Congress.
In particular, it envisages: better control of the elected representatives over its application, new mechanisms ensuring the repayment of the deposited public money, new measures to capture the amount of houses seized due to non-payment, as well as the right to monitor the level of wages paid to managers of rescued companies.
U.S. Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson, House Speaker Nancy Pelosi and the Republican representative at the negotiating table, Senator Judd Gregg, announced the good news just minutes after midnight yesterday, following the conclusion of a two-day negotiation marathon.
"We've made great progress and we've reached an agreement that's going to be effective in the markets," said Henry Paulson, a senior administration official.
“Everything was done to keep the real economy and ordinary Americans safe from the crisis that is taking place on Wall Street,” he said.
"This is a critical point: if we don't, the trauma, chaos and disruption to American daily life will be enormous," Gregg said.
Over the past few hours, negotiations have begun to take a maximum turn for fear of the effect that another failure would have on investor sentiment.
The time limit was set for the markets to open this morning.
Both candidates for President of the United States were invited to the negotiations later, and both expressed rather in favor of the agreement, but did not forget to express their dissatisfaction with the fact that it was necessary to resort to such an extreme solution.
Democratic Senator Barack Obama has credited the addition of an agreement on some measures, particularly one aimed at allowing homeowners to maintain their residence, and measures on the wages of state-rescued workers.
“When we ask taxpayers to take special measures because of the irresponsibility of some people, there is nothing to congratulate.
But these measures are necessary," he explained on television.
His Republican opponent, John McCain, who was asked by another station whether he would vote for the proposed plan, replied: "I'd like to see the details, but I hope so."
“The rough features I’ve read [show] that it’s something that we’re all going to have to go through and make it possible to move forward.
“Choose inaction is simply unacceptable,” he said.
The goal of the $700 billion plan is to buy back dubious claims and risky and unsellable assets of US financial institutions with taxpayers’ money.
The plan comes after 14 months of crisis unleashed by a housing bubble that first led to the collapse of risky mortgages (subprimes), then transferred to other, more widespread forms of loans (PCAAs) and resulted in a cash freeze and the breakdown of banks and financial institutions.
The collapse of the first draft of the agreement last week is the responsibility of the Republican deputies.
Since the Democrats have accepted that the government will only vouch for, but not buy, some of the “toxic” assets of troubled companies, there is a conviction that the impasse is over.
In an effort to reconcile conflicting views in Congress, a provision was added that the government would be able to introduce new fees that would help it recover its deposit if, as a result of the program, it had to take over losses for five years.
The new plan envisages the deposit of the first amount of 250 billion, to which it will be possible to add another 100 billion, if the President deems it necessary.
A further $350 billion should be approved by Congress in a new vote.
In exchange for his help, Washington will receive shares in the rescued companies, which, if profitable, will pay him dividends and which he will be able to sell again when it is all over.
The federal government will have the option of delaying the procedures for seizing real estate related to the loans covered by the plan, as well as setting limits on the amount of appraisals and compensation paid to executives of affected companies.
The drafters of the plan would like to submit it to a vote in the House of Representatives today and in the Senate on Wednesday.
Despite all the efforts, it is not yet clear whether their plan will be green.
Yesterday, votes continued to rise against the project in both the Republican and Democratic camps.
"It's pretty clear that Washington can't hear you," Scott Garrett, a member of the House finance committee, said.
"Yes, we have a serious financial problem.
Yes, there are solutions.
Paying taxes is not a solution.”
Democratic Representative Brad Sherman, the moderator of a group of congressmen dubbed the "skeptics' committee," presents the matter differently, but comes to the same conclusion.
“Four hundred distinguished professors of economics, including three Nobel Prize winners, have written to us: we ask Congress not to be too hasty and to examine carefully which path to take,” he said.
At the same time, it was again confirmed in Europe that this crisis is a global crisis.
Following the end of the emergency meeting, the three Benelux countries announced the partial nationalization of the Fortis banking group for <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>11.2 billion ($16.3 billion).
The intervention by the governments of Belgium, the Netherlands and Luxembourg became necessary after French bank BNP Paribas announced it was withdrawing from the purchase of its competitor, which has been on the verge of collapse since it lost <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2 billion ($2.9 billion) as a result of the crisis of risky loans to buy real estate in the United States.
Fortis employs 85,000 people and is one of Europe’s top 20 banks and top 10 insurers.
"We will not lose this money," said Dutch Finance Minister Wouter Bos.
“In return, we gain the right to vote in a bank and influence.
And that’s what savers and households can appreciate in these uncertain times.”
On the other side of the English Channel, the British government appears to have launched a nationalisation of another bank hit by the financial crisis.
According to the English press, the government was to take over all existing loans from Bradford and Bringley, of which more than 41 billion (US$75.5 billion) were loans to buy real estate.
According to its announcement yesterday, the Spanish bank Santander will buy the branches and accounts of clients of the British bank.
Bradford and Bringley will be the second bank after Northern Rock to be nationalised by the UK government since the start of the financial crisis.
Paul Newman (1925-2008) - Death of a Socially Engaged Icon
His beauty with azure eyes has long been his trump card, according to others a weakness.
Has this American actor emerged with a charming smile from narcissism?
Yes and no.
The shyness, sensitivity, and unfailing talent that was his own also distanced him from the power category that begets real stars.
But what a long-distance runner he was!
Paul Newman died on Friday at the age of 83 at his Connecticut ranch from lung cancer and remains one of the last icons of the fat years of American cinema.
Less grandiose than Brando, to whom he was similar and had long been a kind of rival on the screen, Newman was a more cautious actor, certainly more fragile, but also an apostle of freedom and the breakdown of dramatic conventions.
Mixed blood often gives birth to beautiful children.
Born in Ohio in 1925, his father was a German Jew and his mother was Hungarian.
From these European roots, one of the famous faces of the American dream was born.
Without excessive ego, which is the last sign of quality.
Because in it, the whole country looked in love with self-made mana, a fighter in the war in the Pacific, wounded in the battle, who in the early 1950s studied acting in Yale, then attended the New York Actor's Studio and celebrated triumph in theater, television and soon in film.
The same man who fought for civil rights was also a race car driver who placed second at the Le Mans 24-hour race in 1979, and also a sexual symbol, despite having formed a model couple with actress Joanne Woodward since 1958.
With him also go the shady places of this hidden, discreet, socially engaged star, allergic to the hype of his own show business, which will forever remain somewhat mysterious.
A decent man, in the noblest sense of the word.
Paul Newman’s departure this weekend has left movie lovers dizzy, while his big roles rival each other on the black canvas of memories.
It is followed by more than half a century of the ever-changing American seventh art.
The charming cowboy from Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid (1969), a young man who rejects his sensual wife (Elizabeth Taylor) in The Cat on the Hot Roof, a 1958 Tennessee Williams adaptation, reappears in memory.
From a less distant past (1990), we recall his sensitive Mr. Bridge, troubled in old age by a marriage that did not live up to all expectations.
So many Paul Newmans have gone down in history.
Boxer Rocky Graziano, a battered, violent, unforgettable delinquent from Robert Wise's Somebody Up There Likes Me, a role intended for James Dean, taken over after his death, which brought Newman into real prominence in 1956.
A likeable gangster in the absolutely great The Sting (Scam), Oscar for Best Picture in 1973.
A bitter and vindictive pool player in Robert Rossen's The Hustler (1961), he will portray the same character in Martin Scorsese's The Color of Money, earning him the only Oscar out of seven nominations in 1987.
This face wandering through the ages, it was him.
And he's back.
In his professional career, different eras compete with each other.
Young people know him mainly thanks to the iconic Slap Shot by George Roy Hill (1977) from the role of Reggie Dunlop, an unconventional hockey coach.
Fans met him again in 1994 in The Hudsucker Proxy of the Coen brothers.
He ended his career as the godfather of the Irish Mafia in Sam Mendes' 2003 film Road to Perdition.
Contrary to a few film legends who left the craft fairly soon, Newman remained in the business for a long time, albeit denouncing Hollywood with its glitter, ostentatiousness, and concessions.
French filmmaker Bertrand Tavernier considered it, not without humor, "a living challenge of underplaying", judging that in his performances he pushed the saw too much.
For the beautiful Paul Newman, whose roles came on a platter, the profession was not always so tender.
The first lovers, however, he played less often than the outsiders: neurotics, alcoholics, scoundrels and despairers, whose decline and rebellion were reflected in his perfect features.
As a director, Newman revealed little-known aspects of his shy sensitivity.
His 1968 film Rachel, Rachel (based on the novel by Canadian Margaret Laurence), starring his wife Joanne Woodward, gives a sensitive female portrait full of melancholy.
In 1984, he dedicated the film Harry and Son to his son Scott, whom he had lost to an overdose, a work of shame and sadness.
In a wave of tributes Newman received yesterday, his great friend and former partner Robert Redford (played together on The Sting and Butch Cassidy and the Sundance Kid) lamented, "His presence made my life and this country better."
Generosity, love of life, these are the main characteristics of the deceased actor.
Abandoning his legendary career, he also leaves a great fighter for civil rights, ecology, an independent film, an opponent of the decline of Hollywood.
We were used to seeing his image on bottles of wine vinegar, sauces, cookies and other foods, which may have seemed rather tasteless, although at first it was a gag.
However, the profits from the sale went to the account of his Foundation for Difficult Childhood.
Rather than being swayed by fame, Newman was engaged in society until the very last moment.
He left a letter to his five daughters that read: “Always and to the end, your father was grateful to his happy planet.
It was an honor to be here.”
And it was an honor for us to be able to follow the life path of such a clairvoyant and generous American artist.
And besides, after all, an exemplary citizen.
