The Psychology of Trumping: Why Are We Spending More Money?
In auctions, customers are willing to spend more money, overestimate the goods.
The neurological and economic underpinnings of this familiar – and seemingly irrational – behavior have been revealed to researchers in the fields of neuroscience and economics at New York University.
According to their study, published in the journal Science, people do not want to lag behind in a competition like eBay auctions, so they prefer to pay too high a price.
Research using an experimental auction tried to map the scheme of this "game" in the nervous system.
One group of volunteers gambled, the second group participated in a live auction, using the method of functional magnetic resonance imaging (fMRI) to examine the active areas of the brain of experimental subjects.
In both games, the participants could win money, but when playing at an auction, the important element of which is to win the other side, the whole located under the cerebral cortex, called the striatum, began to work intensively during the loss.
This brain region plays, among many other functions, a role in the "self-reward" mechanism of the nervous system.
Therefore, according to the researchers, the screwing-up of the price can be explained by an attempt to avoid a sharp striat reaction.
To support their theory, members of the research team from among economists conducted a financial cross-sectional survey.
Under different conditions, three groups were bidding against one partner.
The control group was simply told what the fair value of the product in question was and they made the bets.
In addition, members of the other group were promised that if they came out of the game victorious, they would receive an additional $15 as a reward.
The third group received $15 before the auction, but in the event of a loss, its members also lost this money.
The difference between the two groups, therefore, lay in the fact that one emphasized victory and the other was a loss.
However, the members of the group playing "against losing" were willing to go higher than in the control and "winning" group, which confirms the hypothesis of neurologists.
“These results cannot be inferred from any pre-existing economic theory.
Until now, they have explained the phenomena observed in auctions of the joys of victory and the avoidance of risk.
It wasn’t until neurological imaging methods helped us resolve the contradiction between the two theories that we now came up with a third explanation,” said Andrew Schotter, a professor of economics at New York University.
Hepatitis: when to see a doctor?
About half a billion people worldwide suffer from chronic hepatitis B or C infection, and in Hungary this chronic liver disease is listed as one of the leading causes of death.
The number of domestic cases of hepatitis infection is estimated at one hundred thousand, but only seven thousand of them are treated. The reason for this is that patients often do not know that they are infected.
The name hepatitis is a collective name for infectious liver damage caused by various viruses.
There are many similarities in their symptoms, inflammation of the liver and jaundice is characteristic, but the causative agents of the disease and the diseases caused by them differ from each other.
Depending on the causes of the disease, hepatitis viruses are spread in two main ways: hepatitis type A and E in the digestive tract (for example, infected food, water), hepatitis type B, C, D and other viruses by blood and body fluids (sperm, vaginal secretion, saliva).
In any case, travelers should protect themselves by vaccination against virus A and B, there is no vaccine against virus type C.
Symptoms of hepatitis A appear two to three weeks after ingestion of infected food, usually accompanied by nausea, weakness, abdominal discomfort, urge to vomit.
After that, jaundice, lightening of the stools and darkening of the urine will form on the skin and whites of the eyes. Treatment can take up to two to three weeks.
Every year, one million people die worldwide from a more serious type of the disease, liver cancer and liver cirrhosis caused by hepatitis B.
The main reason is that, according to estimates, only one in ten infected is treated with medication.
Also, hepatitis C can have very serious consequences: if left untreated, it can lead to liver cirrhosis or liver cancer.
Most infected do not even know about their disease, the causative agent of the disease destroys liver cells insidiously, and so the first symptoms appear in many cases only in 20-30 years.
Therefore, early prevention, the implementation of regular depistration is very important.
In three groups, the disease occurs much more often than average: among people who underwent blood transfusions before 1991, among drug users, and among people with tattoos.
Currently, the estimated global number of individuals infected with chronic hepatitis C virus is 200 million.
Since the disease can already be proven by routine laboratory examination, a person should contact his general practitioner if he notices any symptom of unknown origin.
With early detection, the disease is curable, the virus can be removed from the body to prevent infection and prevent the development of cancer.
September 30th is World Hepatitis Day, which was first organized in 2004 by organizations representing the sick worldwide.
Its aim is to draw attention to chronic inflammation of the liver caused by these viruses, the causes of its occurrence and the importance of early recognition of the disease.
