Intelligent car imitates bumblebee flight
What would be the best method of developing collision-preventable technologies, if not imitating obstacle detectors found in the natural world?
For example, with bees.
The initial strategic idea of the surprising project, presented at the Japanese trade fair CEATEC, was inspired by Nissan engineers bumblebees. It was about how to build a new generation of systems to prevent collisions.
In collaboration with the University of Tokyo, Nissan has designed a biomimetic robotic control system type BR23C, a robotic mini-car that is equipped with the characteristics of bees, with the ultimate goal of helping to create a system that can eliminate all precipitation.
"During the flight, each bee creates its own personal space of oval shape, which is actually very similar to our safety protective packaging," explained Kazuhiro Doi, general director of the brand for technology PR and R&D.
An important role is played by compound eyes, which allow bees to see in all directions at an angle of vision of more than 300 degrees.
To copy the function of the compound eye, engineers reached for the idea of a laser rangefinder.
It identifies obstacles up to 2 meters ahead of BR23C in a 180-degree field of view, calculates their distance and sends a signal to the on-board microprocessor, which immediately turns into an operation aimed at preventing a collision.
The obstacle is captured within a fraction of a second, then the robot car begins to imitate the movements of the bee, and by turning the wheels to the extent necessary to prevent a collision, it immediately changes direction.
Unlike any existing system, this maneuver takes place in a completely instinctive way.
“If this were not the case, a robotic car would not be able to react fast enough to avoid obstacles,” explains Toshiyuki Ando, head of the Mobility and Robotic Car Project.
It must respond instinctively and immediately, as this technology suits the most vulnerable and innermost layer of safety protective packaging, within which a collision is currently considered inevitable.
The whole process must reflect what the bee is doing to avoid other bees.
This process should not take longer than a blink of an eye.
However, unlike bees, this movement cannot be upwards, downwards or diagonally, it can only be two-dimensional and only in the direction in which the wheels can be turned.
Instead of the endless possibilities offered to bees when avoiding, only the possibility of rotational movement, acceleration and deceleration was applied in the case of a robotic car.
The BR23C uses lithium-polymer batteries that are lighter and have a higher energy density, which means they have a longer lifespan than lithium-ion variants.
According to Ando, instinctive, intelligent response is important, not the ability to process, much less store data.
This mechanism must process and respond to only a few incoming signals per second.
It does not need to store and react using intuitive logic based on data from previous maneuvers, so it constantly uses only memory of a few kilobytes.
It does not need memory with giga- or megabyte capacity.
This is the first step towards developing a technology for immediate avoidance that Nissan estimates could hit mass-produced cars within a decade.
Another possibility of application may be the connection of the unit with the GPS satellite navigation system, which, after avoiding obstacles in the way, would lead the motorist to the given final goal.
