The $700 billion economic rescue package bill, which is to be split into several instalments and which aims to buy back low-quality bank loans, is already in writing.
In the first round, half of the amount will be used.
After further negotiations, which ended just after midnight on Saturday, congressional leaders reached an agreement in a days-long debate on a $700 billion rescue package, Reuters reported.
"We have made significant progress," said Nancy Pelosi, the Democratic speaker of the House of Representatives, who said only a draft agreement remained.
Both presidential candidates, Barack Obama and John McCain, also supported the compromise on the package.
Treasury Secretary Henry Paulson said: “The program will work and it will be effective, but more needs to be done.”
The written form of the package was published before the opening of the Asian markets on Sunday at 8 p.m. Washington time (that is, on Monday at 2 a.m. Central European time), but it did not cause any special rise in the stock exchanges.
The bill, known as the 2008 Emergency Economic Stabilization Act, will be put to the vote on Monday, before being voted on by the House of Representatives and then by the Senate.
President George W. Bush spoke to Pelosi on Saturday night, and news of the deal was also welcomed at the White House.
“We are pleased with the progress that has been made this evening and greatly appreciate both parties’ efforts to stabilize our financial markets and protect our economy,” White House spokesman Tony Fratto said in a statement.
The program differs from the Bush administration’s original proposal to spend a total of $700 billion on the purchase of substandard mortgage-backed securities.
It is now possible to spend a maximum of half of the $700 billion in the first round, so that the $250 billion will be used as soon as Congress is expected to decide on the matter on Monday, and the Treasury Department will buy mortgage-backed securities for them that are rated as substandard, and the fate of the remaining $100 billion will then depend on the president’s decision.
The program will be overseen by a special board, which will also include the chairman of the Federal Reserve Bank.
Spending the second half of the $700 billion will depend on the next decision of Congress.
The Ministry of Finance may, within the meaning of the law, apply a combined tactic: it can simultaneously buy low-quality loans, mortgages and securities secured by mortgages, or other "poisonous" loans.
The purchase may take place within the framework of auctions and directly, said the competent representatives of the Ministry.
The legal standard will allow the companies concerned to participate in an insurance programme in which the Ministry of Finance provides them with a guarantee for funds constituting cause for concern, for which the company will then pay a price corresponding to the amount of the expected damage.
As Henry Paulson said, the law provides the necessary funds to meet the urgent requirements of the US financial system to spend up to $700 billion, whether it is a large-scale purchase of bad funds, their insurance or to prevent the systemic risk associated with the collapse of one of the major financial institutions.
“We will take the necessary steps to be ready to implement the law as soon as it is signed.”
On the other hand, the heads of banks that are in trouble and are waiting for state help can count on the government cutting their severance pay – which in overseas slang is simply called a “golden parachute”.
Their payments will be limited only in certain cases, moreover, these restrictions will depend on the manner of assistance provided by the ministry.
The restriction essentially means that if the ministry purchases as part of the auction, a tax surcharge will be imposed on gold parachutes unless the fallen bank directors are sent straight to retirement.
In the case of direct purchase of substandard loans, the government will aggressively intervene in order to ensure that the money for management is not excessive.
It is necessary to add that the existing contracts on gold parachutes will not change, the restriction applies only to new contracts, which should be another incentive to participate in the program.
“This is the first time in U.S. history that there will be a legal restriction on the remuneration of CEOs,” House Financial Services Committee Chairman Barney Frank said in a statement.
In addition, the State will be entitled to a shareholding in the banks participating in the programme, which will reduce the risk of taxpayers, because once the economy and the rescued bank are on their feet, they can make a profit on this transaction.
In the next five years, the President must submit to Congress a proposal setting out how the expected losses from the financial sector can be repaid to taxpayers.
On both sides, of course, there were voices expressing doubts about the plan.
“That’s not what the American people asked us to do, that’s not what taxpayers’ dollars are going to protect,” said California Republican Rep. Darrell Issa.
His Democratic Ohio counterpart, Mary Kaptur, said the legislation was pushed by those responsible for the Wall Street crash.
Industrial prices continue to rise
Domestic sales prices in the industry increased by 0.1 percent in August 2008 compared to the previous month, and by 12.9 percent compared to August 2007, the Central Statistical Office said.
Export sales prices in the industry were 1.1 percent higher compared to July 2008, a year-on-year decrease of 3.9 percent.
Industrial production prices, as a cause of changes in domestic and export prices compared to the previous month, increased by 0.7 percent, year-on-year they increased by 3.2 percent.
Domestic sales prices in the industry increased only minimally compared to the previous month, by 0.1 percent.
Domestic sales prices in the manufacturing sector also increased slightly, by 0.1 percent, compared to July.
The largest increase in prices occurred in August 2008 in the leather and footwear industry (2.8 percent), mainly due to the monthly increase in prices in the production of bag and saddlery products by 4.6 percent and the production of footwear by 2.5 percent, respectively.
The higher price level of plastic and chemical raw materials caused a significant monthly increase in prices in the production of chemical materials and products (1.6%).
Prices have fallen in the oil processing (1.4 per cent), electrical machinery and equipment (0.9 per cent) and - to a minimum - wood processing (0.1 per cent).
Prices in the field of paper production and publishing and printing activities have not changed.
In other sectors of the manufacturing industry, we measured price increases in the range of 0.2 - 0.9 percent.
In the electricity, gas and water production and distribution sector, which has a large weight in the domestic sales of industry, prices rose by 0.3 percent in August, mainly due to the continuing impact of the officially established increase in gas prices taking place from 1 July.
In a 12-month comparison of domestic sales in individual sectors of the manufacturing industry, prices rose the most in the professional oil processing sector (32.4 percent).
In the metalworking sector, a 13.2% increase was observed, followed by a 11% increase in prices in the production of food products, beverages and tobacco products, which has a decisive weight.
Prices decreased in the textile and textile products sectors (2.5%) and in the production of electrical machinery and apparatus (0.3%).
In other sectors of the manufacturing industry, the price growth rate ranged between 0.6 and 9.1 percent.
Overall, manufacturing prices rose by 10.2 percent last year.
Prices in the electricity, gas and water generation and distribution sectors exceeded prices from the previous year by 18.7 percent.
In terms of segmentation by industry focus, domestic sales showed the highest monthly price increase (0.7%) in the physical asset sectors in August.
In the sectors producing consumer goods, prices increased by 0.3 percent, in the energy processing and downstream sectors, prices did not change compared to the previous month.
In August 2008, the largest increase in prices compared to the same month of the previous year was observed in the energy processing and downstream sectors (16.8 per cent).
In the sectors producing consumer goods, we measured a price increase of 6.8 percent, while in the case of tangible assets, prices decreased by 1.4 percent.
Export sales prices of industrial products measured in forints increased by 1.1 percent in August compared to the previous month, falling by 3.9 percent in the 12-month comparison.
Our domestic currency weakened by 1.7 percent against the euro in one month, 7.1 percent against the dollar, 7.5 percent against the euro in August 2007, and 15.9 percent against the dollar.
