Occupational accidents, Napolitano: "Resolute prevention"
Every day, 2,500 work-related injuries occur in Italy, three people die and twenty-seven remain permanently disabled.
The Inail figures confirm that in 2007 there were approximately 1,200 deaths as a result of work-related injuries.
These values testify to the seriousness of the phenomenon, which remains one of the main causes of death and causes almost twice as many deaths as homicides.
In order to reawaken the attention of institutions, social and information media on this dramatic problem, Anmil is celebrating today, in all Italian regions, the 58th National Day of Victims of Occupational Injuries, set for the second Sunday in October.
"The alarming data disseminated by Anmil and the same tragic news these days confirm the importance of the issue of occupational safety," President Giorgio Napolitano said in a report sent to President Anmil, the National Association for the Mutilated and Disabled for Work, Pietro Mercandelli.
The Head of State expresses his deep admiration for the constant joint efforts for safety at work, for the protection of injured workers, for assistance to the families of the victims and for the participation of public opinion.
“Naturally, an outraged ‘enough’ has been raised, sincerely shared in the face of tragedies that in their scope cause a stir in the media and the participation of public opinion, but everyday reality again offers us dramatic cases, even repeating itself in its dynamics.”
Napolitano makes no secret of the fact that "there is undoubtedly a resource problem here: it is crucial to invest in training and awareness.
Numerous initiatives in the field of education are of particular importance in order to raise awareness among young people facing the world of work.
It is necessary to draw attention to this phenomenon, not to give up because of its alarming social severity, to apply and improve legislative norms.
Chamber President Gianfranco Fini, for his part, stressed "how the phenomenon of death as a result of a work accident creates an absolutely critical social state, how it offends the conscience of each of us and forces all institutions to make a convincing effort towards the necessary end of this state."
"As for the data on work-related injuries, they seem to show a certain positive turnaround, but this does not deny that the number of deaths as a result of work-related injuries is alarming in any case," President Anmilu Pietro Mercandelli said.
"We would not want this 'effort to reduce' to lead to less attention, because the moment the attention stops, tragedy breaks out.
“We believe that there is generally still too little being done to stop the problem of injuries, and there are many activities that can have an impact on this problem.
It is necessary, in our opinion, to increase controls and inspections, but also to intervene more strongly in the area of training of workers, right from school age."
"There is still a need for further efforts," he added, "in terms of communication and participation of public opinion.
But above all, a greater sense of responsibility on the part of employers towards a phenomenon which constitutes an exceptional social phenomenon is needed.
Mercandelli finally declared that this was a progressive degeneration of the levels of the right to compensation assumed for working victims and the “displacement of supportive care” that the system has been coming to in recent years.
“The aim is therefore to give back to the worker the guarantee of insurance,” he added, “because the fate of those who harm themselves must not depend on spontaneity or gifting from time to time by the legislator.”
Mp3 Players Accused, Expose Hearing Risk
Listening to loud music for an extended period of time and using portable music devices as an MP3 player can cause permanent hearing damage.
According to a notice published today by the European Commission, which in an official report extended in Brussels quotes the opinion of the Committee on Science on health risks that have recently emerged and have been identified (Csrseri) by the EU.
“From this scientific opinion – we read in the notes – it follows that 5-10% of those who for at least five years listen to music using portable musical instruments, weekly for more than an hour a day and keep the device at a high volume, risk permanent hearing loss.”
“I am concerned that such a large number of young people, who often use portable musical instruments and mobile phones at high acoustic levels, can unknowingly damage their hearing in an irreparable way,” admits Meglena Kuneva.
“From the scientific findings,” the leader continues, “there is a clear risk and we need to react quickly.
The most important thing is that we need to stimulate consumers and make this information public.
We must continue to re-examine existing control systems in the light of this scientific finding to make them fully effective and to keep pace with new technology.”
Brussels asked the Independent Scientific Committee to investigate the problem, given the high use of portable musical instruments and the increasing number of young people exposed to noise of this origin.
"Scientists confirm that concerns need to be raised and the European Commission will now examine, together with the other Members and the parties that raised the issue, what measures could possibly be put in place to better protect children and young people from exposure to noise caused by portable musical instruments and similar devices."
There is already a European safety standard that limits the noise level of portable musical instruments to 100 dB, but there are growing concerns about hearing damage that can be caused by excessive exposure to similar forms of noise.
It is possible to greatly reduce these damages by looking for solutions such as reducing the level and duration of exposure.
In its opinion, the Eu Scientific Committee states that users of portable musical instruments, when using loud music (more than 89 decibels) for only five hours a week, will exceed the currently applicable limits corresponding to the maximum permitted noise in the workplace.
Those who listen to music in such conditions for an extended period of time risk permanent hearing loss after five years.
This problem should concern 5-10% of users of such devices, and their number can be estimated between 2.5 and 10 million people in the EU.
