Elites in Danger
This phenomenon manifested itself a few days ago, when the House of Representatives voted against the $700 billion rescue plan presented by the White House: a significant portion of Americans were more interested in punishing Wall Street than saving the economy.
This is confirmed by yesterday’s New York Times, which informs us that the current crisis is dividing the Republican party, increasingly divided between its old soul, the East Coast, a milder, accommodating federal institutions and the business community, and its new soul, which, on the contrary, is conservative, hostile to “those from Washington” and, above all, to the world of finance.
The soul that arrogantly expressed itself in the vote I spoke of at the beginning.
But this is just an example of the changes, the big changes, that the current economic earthquake is already showing: not only in the United States, but throughout the West, and maybe not just here.
Both in the US and in Europe, this crisis seems to act as an accelerator of phenomena that have been incubated for a long time, which are solidifying in the new climate and finally coming to light.
The first of these phenomena is the re-actualization, the extraordinary revival of the market, the double category of the Power-State in relation to a certain re-nationalization of the economy.
The crisis is indeed a crisis of banking and financial institutions, which, of course, have strong ties abroad, but in which the budgets of people and families living in a single country, in a single state, are primarily included.
At the same time, this has created a political problem for those who run it: how to respond to the difficulties and protests of people and families who are, among other things, voters.
In short, the crisis appears to be economic world-wide, but politically almost exclusively national.
Political internationality seems to be largely out of the question or has little to add: the European Union, which is divided, as always, between different interests and different state strategies, and which is unable to decide on a single common political line, has given obvious proof.
And so everyone is waiting for the intervention of the government of each individual state, rescue plans, market recovery, new rules and, most importantly, the distribution of funds: at the moment when we get into distress, only the states have the economic means, the amount of financial resources, to be able to try to put everything in order.
It also possesses the necessary means and powers to use them: two sources of immense value, under certain circumstances, which perhaps no market and no international organization will ever be able to dispose of to a similar extent.
This new emphases, which the crisis places on the state-national element, is, after all, in perfect harmony with the ever-increasing importance which the recent economic progress attempts to attribute to one factor closely connected with it: territoriality.
Paradoxically, in fact, while we were convinced that we had entered the kingdom satiated, increasingly sophisticated technology, immaterial, while we were convinced that global finance was already destined to rule the world, all of a sudden we realized that our future, on the contrary, would have to deal more and more with such little intangible things as water, grain.
All things, who would say it, can be transported from one place on earth to another, but they are in any case connected, absolutely, to a limited space, territory.
So, whoever becomes their ruler certainly has many more cards up his sleeve than those who are not, and who have the misfortune of living in a place without grain, without oil and without water.
I come to the second novelty, which, however, predicts a breakthrough.
Whoever speaks of territory, state, government, inevitably speaks of politics, that is, of leadership.
Taking into account the economic crisis, two convergent phenomena appear to be forming.
On the one hand, the realization that there is an objective need for authoritarian leadership, a request for someone who could take the situation.
On the other hand, a wave of discrediting of existing leaderships, especially economic ones, which turned out to be equally unsatisfactory and full of dark places.
And together, something even more profound and, in a sense, unsettling: the discredit, the impatience, the sense of incompetence and absence that is trying to dominate the entire ruling class in more and more Western countries.
For it seems that convictions are spreading more and more among the broad masses of the population than that their actions should be the same as the ideas of the hitherto popular elite, as their way of feeling and being, as their culture in the true sense of the word, that the elite has already outlived its time and is indifferent to the opinions of the majority.
The demand for leadership may simply be feeding a branch out of the underworld, but the strong movement for the removal of the ruling classes and the traditional political order is manifested in sudden electoral "revolts" or in unexpected changes in collective moods in the last and most recent time, from the conservative rise of the Great Congress in Great Britain to the rise of the Great Patriotic War in Great Britain.
We have the impression that the traditional elites, their parties, their programs, but also their ceremonies, their newspapers, their accredited intelligence, one would say their format, have growing problems to understand, that is, to represent, which, not from today, is being created in the deep layers of Western societies, and that the economic crisis is strengthening again, growing, potentially too large.
Before that, it would be an exaggeration to speak of a permanent “mass revolt.”
But we certainly can’t say that it means having your eyes open.
Super glue to walk on the walls
Overcome the laws of gravity thanks to super glue and in the future walk on the walls as Spiderman.
This is an object of various American research centers, and now a team of four institutes has come very close to it.
Scientists have managed to keep a 100-kilogram body glued to a vertical wall with a sticker of only 2.5 square centimeters.
The American journal Science has published the findings of some researchers at the University of Dayton, Akron, the Georgia Institute of Technology and the Air Force Research Laboratory.
The material, which was invented by a team of researchers, is the development of materials already in existence that use a special carbon structure called carbon dwarf tubes.
“The glue base can be imagined as a series of tubes laid out like an ordered pile of spaghetti,” explains Zhong Lin Wang of the Georgia Institute of Technology in Atlanta.
The scientists were inspired by the legs of the gecko, covered with microscopic hairs that allow the animal to ensure perfect adhesion.
Tests carried out on various materials such as glass, Teflon and glass paper have shown that the new glue is ten times stronger than the legs of these reptiles and at the same time "simply peels off the wall," explains Liming Dai, a researcher at the University of Dayton's Faculty of Engineering.
-"This material could be useful as a temporary glue" adds Liming Dai.
Perhaps to walk on walls like Spiderman? Perhaps, but researchers are thinking of a far less fascinating use as a connection of electrical appliances, because dwarf carbon pipes are conductors of heat and electricity.
Other applications could relate to aerospace engineering.
So far, no superheroes.
FURTHER RESEARCH – The University of Berkeley, California, is also researching a new adhesive.
In an article in the Journal of the American Chemical Society, Californian scientists introduced a microfiber-formed adhesive like hair that cleans itself from dust by moving it over a surface to still maintain a perfect fit.
