the Nobel Prize in Economics to Paul Krugman
The Nobel Prize was awarded to Paul Krugman for his studies of commercial models and localization of economic activities.
Krugman is a 55-year-old New Kenyan who teaches at the University of Priceton and is a well-known editor of the New York Times.
Krugman is one of the most important critics of the Bush administration’s foreign, economic, and political actions.
A few months after the September 2001 assassinations, in the days of Enron's bankruptcy, Krugman predicted in a New York Times op-ed that the second event would be, in terms of implications for the history of the United States, much more important than the first.
A prediction that caused quite a bit of controversy and that had been blamed on him for years, but which turned out to be accurate.
“I am surprised and shocked at the speed at which collapses like Enron and Worldcom have disappeared from the public eye,” Krugman said in a statement.
According to Lorenzo Bini Smaghi of the Central European Bank’s Executive Committee, Krugman is an “economy of great importance” but also a popularizer who has a “very aggressive style, especially critical of the excesses of the Bush liberal administration.”
Open Office, we have the third edition of the "anti-Microsoft" package.
It’s the day of the release of Open Office.org 3.0, an open source personal production package that aims to reach more and more users, from home to office, from professionals to public administration, as a free alternative to the more familiar Microsoft Office.
After about a year of work by volunteers, controlled by SUN Microsystem, the new Open Office will be presented to the general public with various novelties: the welcome screen and the revised and improved opening window will be supplemented with other, much more substantial ones, such as compatibility for the Apple Mac OS X operating system and support for the new ODF (Open Document Format) 1.2, the latest version.
The emphasis is also placed on cooperation with the Office 2007 package, Open Office is able to open the document with the new Microsoft extension (.docx, .xlsx, .pptx).
Interesting are the special features of some models, such as what allows you to reduce the size of the PowerPoint presentation, useful for example for electronic transmission, or the ability to transfer a PDF file to a graphic design model and preserve the original appearance of the page.
From this point of view, we can still create "PDF hybrids" documents that are similar to typical Adobe graphics and have the properties of a spreadsheet or text program.
Collaboration is an element that has received many improvements within application programs: in excel, it is possible to work together between different users and avoid conflicts on changes, in the text program, each co-worker is assigned one color to comments, so that there is a clearer identification in the revision phase.
Some companies are also working on transferring some of the features of Open Office to the Web (on the cloud), and in the coming weeks they should present a definitive result.
The Italian version can be downloaded at http://it.openoffice.org/download/3.0.0/download300.html, it was added to the English version, which is located on the mirror since Friday.
In addition to Windows and Mac OS, as usual, the package is also available for the Linux operating system.
Also, the installation cd can be sent home or to the workplace on request.
And if the topic of freelancing can be a drag to expand in homes, it is on the business area of Open Office that the package relies a lot, and can already count on a variety of projects implemented in public administration and in schools.
And there is also a range of training, consulting and assistance services ideal for small and medium-sized businesses, which could open up business prospects.
Open Office consists of five main models: Writer, for video writing replacing Word; Calc is a spreadsheet that aims to replace Excel; Impress for Powerpoint-like presentations; Dbase, as in the case of the more famous Access, is a program that allows you to work on databases; Draw, in the end, is a graphical model.
The goal for 2008 is to reach 5 million downloads, and considering that to date we are almost 3 million and 600 thousand, with the release of the new version it is possible that this estimated number can be overcome.
