Immigrants: The New York Times is complaining, is Italy racist?
Italy "as a country of emigrants has only in the last house turned into a priority target of immigrants" received with resistance.
Does it turn a beautiful country into a nation of racists? That’s how the New York Times, a long-running article devoted to the debate on racism in Italy, began with the case of young Abdul William Guibre, originally from Burkina Faso, who was killed last month in Milan for stealing a box of cookies.
This case highlights what the New York Times defines as the “Northern Paradox”: the northern areas are also where “more integration and more work” is registered, but also “the strongest anti-immigrant sentiment in the country and the strongest support for the Northern League.”
To confirm rising tensions between Italians and immigrants, the NYT cites cases of intolerance from Milan, Parma, Rome, Ciampino and Castel Volturna.
Not only that.
The new legislation demanded by the Lega, which seeks to curb immigration and facilitate the expulsion of illegal immigrants, is also cited as an example of the changing climate in Italy.
The trend highlighted by both the Pope and the President of the Republic: “Giorgio Napolitano, after meeting with Benedetto XVI in Quirinale, asked that the state and the Church work together to defeat racism.”
Students victims of expensive rentals - up to 900 euros per room
The rental market for university students is not aware of the crisis.
According to the latest research by Sunia, a department for tenants, renting a single room can cost a student in Milan up to 900 euros, in Florence 700, in Naples 650, in Rome 600.
“The phenomenon has already reached such proportions that entire layers of students have lost the right to study due to the overall too high prices that their families would have to bear,” explains Laura Mariani, head of the Sunia Study Office, “in this city, high demand from students has distorted the market in such a way that it has triggered a process of price increases that has been increasing even for residents.”
In most cases, rental offers contain several offenses: contracts in a free manner, unregistered, without limited rent, and associated sublease.
An exceptional intervention is needed for Sunji, which could regulate prices thanks to the tax revision.
If we look at the details of the research, we will see that in Milan, in the Brianza area, about 450 euros are needed for one bed, for a single room it is paid from a minimum price of 650 (the Bande Nere zone) through an average value of 800 (the Lambiate, Udine and Fiera zones) to a maximum of 900 (the Vittoria zone).
In Florence, one bed costs an average of 350/400 euros, one room about 700.
In Bologna, where students are concentrated in zones close to the university, they need 250/280 euros per bed in a double room, from 370 to 500 in a single room.
In Rome in the central university zones (San Lorenzo, Piazza Bologna) they want about 600 euros per single room, 450 bed in double.
Values are slightly lower (<0xE2><0x82><0xAC>550 per single) in zones close to other universities (Ostiense and Cinecitt<0xC3><0xA0>).
We save only if we move to the peripheral areas: 300 euros per bed and 450 for a single room in the zones of Prenestina, Centocelle and the like.
In Naples, a bed costs <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>300/450, a room from <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>400 to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>600, with the highest prices in the Policlinic, Vomero and Colli Aminei zones.
In Bari, they want 250/350 euros for a bed, at least 350 euros for a single room.
In smaller cities, prices are certainly lower, but they have a greater impact on the economy of citizens.
In cities like Perugia, where the most common phenomenon is rent for students from countries outside the European Union, one more anomaly is finally recorded: an increase of about 25-30% of the fee they want for foreign students, compared to Italian ones.
Farewell to the old cinema Paradiso, the city cancels the historic halls
Cinematographic historical halls are closing in favor of Multiplex.
“A city without cinemas is like a blind man, like a face without eyes.”
The film, offered by director Giuseppe Tornator, successfully documents what is happening in large Italian urban centers, as well as in rural towns.
The process of restricting cinemas, the birth of large multi-halls in the suburbs and the subsequent disappearance of mono-halls in the central zones of cities, is one of the events that seem inevitable and irreversible, but also has all the hallmarks of a true cultural crime.
“It’s like losing a friend, a friend, with whom we shared a bit of a journey and a lot of emotions,” says New Cinema director Paradiso, a film that won the Tornator an Oscar and a grand jury prize 20 years ago because of a film that lost its way in Cannes.
The values obtained by Anec, the main association of operators, speak clearly: in the last five years, the doors of 316 cinemas of the traditional type have closed, and the highest bill was paid mainly by the halls in the most important cities: 10 less in Florence, 9 less in Milan, Naples, Bologna and Rome, 6 less in Turin, 5 less in Palermo.
Among the regions most affected by closures is Emilia-Romagna, with the loss of 82 cinemas, followed by Tuscany (44) and Lombardy (41).
And proof that the first responsible for their disappearance is the emergence of the multiplex is precisely these three Italian regions, which have registered the highest number of new cinema multi-rooms: 195 more canvases in Lombardy in the last five years, 81 in both Tuscany and Emilia-Romagna.
“The Italian approach has evolved irrationally,” says Paolo Protti, president of Anecu, “it is useful to create new structures, but it would be necessary to guarantee that the existing ones will survive, because when one cinema in the city closes, not all its visitors are willing to move to a multiplex.
Then let us not even talk about the insufficient subsidy to the fund for the benefit of the operators: the previous national debt is about 10 million euros.
From a moral and ethical point of view, it is a shame that the government does not respect existing laws.
Between <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>16 million and <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>18 million per year would be needed to support the sector.”
Interesting is the case of Bologna, the first Italian city to be concerned with closures and which decided to find a way out by signing a protocol between the municipality and Anec, the first of its kind in Italy to protect and promote small cinemas both in historical centers and in the suburbs.
Among the planned standards are tax relief steps for the benefit of operators and benefits for the audience in terms of mobility: spectators will be able to enter the zone with limited traffic and will have special prices to stop and in some parking lots.
“I like this initiative,” says Giuseppe Tornatore, “and I hope that other cities will follow Bologna’s example by introducing other measures.”
However, it is certain that in order to stand against the great power of the multiplex, traditional halls must improve the quality of sound and image, because today's audience is more demanding.
The defense of traditional cinema is a topic that has always been important: the closure of the Super Cinema in Bagheria, the place of my childhood and adolescence, was the spark that convinced me to establish the "New Paradiso Cinema", which I had been thinking about for 10 years.
I have lived in Rome for 25 years, and when I walk in front of the already closed Rialto or Quirinale in the street Nazionale, where I shared so many emotions that I did not have to look at the inscriptions blackened with dust, I turn to the other side.”
Connection between the politician and the mafia group 'ndrangheta, the mayor Gioie Tauro in prison
"The mayor of Gioia Tauro was willing to adjust the municipal elections according to the interests of the Piromalli mafia group."
The charges brought by the Anti-Mafia Directorate in Calabria against Mayor and Vice-Mayor Gioia Tauro Giorgio Dal Torrione e Rosario Schiavone and Mayor Rosarno Carlo Martelli, imprisoned this morning for their external cooperation with the mafia organization, are grave.
Also in handcuffs are Gioacchino Piromalli, an old middleman between the clan and the public administration, and his grandson, a lawyer, a namesake of the boss, already accused of committing mafia-type crimes, sentenced to 10 million euros in damages.
“They ignored all legal and moral norms, as well as common sense,” state prosecutors wrote, when two local authorities expressed their willingness to pay for consultations with lawyer Piromalli.
“This would allow the mafia group,” the judges write, “to officially enter the city’s offices and facilitate the already vast possibilities of control and management of the public administration.”
President of the Calabrian Regional Commission Agazio Loiero does not hide that "there are many secret agreements between local institutions and the organized criminal underworld in his region: "There are areas where the concentration of the mafia is stronger than in others, where secret agreements are inevitable.
But we also have many local politicians who resist the pressures of the ‘ndrangheta,’ heroes who are still unsullied.”
The arrests this morning follow an incarceration in July last year, by which police showed that the Piromalli mafia group had received the final hit.
Since the end of April last year - the city council of Gioii Tauro has been dissolved since 1991, the reason was also the then assumed connection between organized crime and local government - local politicians were deprived of functions in the municipal administration.
Giorgio Dal Torrione, chairman of the Christian Democrats, who at the time of the dissolution was elected head of the center-right coalition after a narrow election in May.
He was screaming about the scandal when the Prefecture ordered the dissolution of the municipal council.
He called then-Deputy Interior Minister Marco Minniti to account and accused him of having designed everything for political reasons, but judges in a prison order signed this morning explain that the mafia group has even gone so far as to ask for a change to the A3 motorway project.
Other interrogations ordered against Dal Torrion, the public prosecutors wrote, showed "the willingness to shift the demands of the businessman, the representative of some larger group very close, as is generally known, to Piromalli and to adapt the public administration elections to the interests of the mafia group."
When energy is born from the waves, the big ones come into play.
It is an infinite deposit that covers more than 70% of the Earth’s surface and is now being discovered by the world’s major energy companies.
Waves, currents, tides, tides are new sources of inexhaustible energy, on which the eyes of giants such as Chevron, which is now trying to lay hands on these sources, cling.
The ability to generate energy from the movements of the sea has been studied for more than a hundred years, and in the 1970s, in connection with the first oil crisis, research intensified.
When the price of oil went down around 1980, the idea of using marine energy went away. But now environmental organizations and a new increase in the price of oil gave the sector a new impetus.
The World Energy Council (WEC) in London in 2007 stated that approximately 15 percent of the world’s electricity consumption could be covered by the use of the motion of the waves of the seas.
This amount would be twice the amount of energy currently produced in nuclear power plants.
In addition, there are currents and tides.
The Giants are attacking.
The company that bet on marine energy was Enersis, which in 2005 agreed to build facilities in northern Portugal.
When this plan was announced, it looked like a huge revolutionary step.
After two years of betting on marine energy, more and more companies are betting on marine energy rather than traditional energy.
“Chevron is studying ocean energy technologies,” said a spokesman for a company connected to the United States oil giant, in the Wall Street Journal, “and they’re thinking about working with us.”
The cooperation we are considering concerns obtaining a permit from the U.S. Energy Commission, which is necessary for the launch of a marine energy project in Alaska.
We cannot underestimate this signal, especially when we consider that it is in Alaska that the US continues to extract oil, and recently President Bush came up with a plan for new drilling.
In addition to Chevron, Verdant Power Inc. of New York and Ocean Power of New Jersey are tracking the trace of marine energy, and the sums invested so far, although not known in detail, show an increasing interest, according to observers.
The technology that needs to be developed.
Experts talk about the technology, which is still in its infancy, because it is not known what impact the use of marine energy will have on the environment.
So far, facilities in Portugal and some in Scotland are small in size and do not appear to be causing major ecosystem problems.
However, for greater energy production, it is necessary to use technologies with a greater impact on the environment.
The methods are different: Ocean Power, for example, uses a system of buoys that are interconnected.
The force of the waves, which moves with the buoys up and down, is changed with the help of cylinders and cylinders to the hydraulic pressure inside these buoys.
The pressure spins the turbine, which supplies energy to the generator.
The energy gets to the shore by submarine cables.
For now, there are four facilities of this type in the project phase, which are only waiting for federal approval, and part of the energy could be used for military purposes.
Verdant Power, on the other hand, is already generating power for the shopping center and parking lot using six offshore turbines in New York’s East River.
The movement of water during the tide causes the turbines to rotate, which feed the generator with this rotating motion.
Verdant said they have a long list of clients who are waiting for the necessary authorization to use this energy.
After the waves, after the tide and after the tide.
Of particular interest at this point is the potential for tides, say the Institute for Electricity Research.
Although it is an incoherent factor, tides are more predictable than wind, sun, or waves, and thus more reliable as a source of energy.
States such as New York, Maine and Alaska, along with other coastal states, have already invested $7 and a half million in 2008 and have forecast investments of up to $35 million for 2009.
